TaskScheduler

A lightweight multi-threaded task scheduling system for Linux designed for efficient background job execution and concurrency experimentation.

This project focuses on understanding how operating systems handle task distribution, worker threads, and asynchronous workloads. It is intended as a learning-focused systems programming project that demonstrates how schedulers coordinate tasks across multiple threads.

TaskScheduler can be used to:
	•	distribute workloads across worker threads
	•	process background jobs asynchronously
	•	experiment with Linux concurrency patterns
	•	learn how scheduling systems work internally

⸻

Features
	•	Multi-threaded worker pool
	•	FIFO task queue
	•	Asynchronous job execution
	•	Lightweight and minimal dependencies
	•	Designed for Linux environments
	•	Educational implementation of scheduling concepts

⸻

Why This Project Exists

Modern systems rely heavily on task schedulers to efficiently run workloads in the background. Examples include:
	•	operating systems
	•	build systems
	•	job runners
	•	web servers
	•	distributed computing platforms

This project demonstrates a simplified version of how those schedulers work internally.

The goal is to explore:
	•	thread management
	•	task queues
	•	synchronization
	•	concurrency safety